{# Agent task: apply an approved change plan to an existing skill. #}
# Apply the approved change plan

The user has approved a change plan in
`design-review-update`. Apply it exactly — nothing more,
nothing less.

## Inputs

- Approved plan: `{{ vars.design_path }}` (matches
  `schemas/design-author-update.yaml`).
- Skill on disk: `{{ vars.skill_dir }}` — `fs_read` the
  current state of any file in `change_plan.files[]` before
  editing.

## Task

For each entry in `change_plan.files[]`:

1. Read `path`, `action`, `summary`, and (if present)
   `rationale` and `content_outline`.
2. Apply the change:
   - **`action: created`** — write a new file at
     `{{ vars.skill_dir }}/<path>` with content matching
     `summary` (and `content_outline` when provided as a
     starting draft).
   - **`action: modified`** — edit the existing file at
     `{{ vars.skill_dir }}/<path>` to implement the
     `summary`. Preserve unrelated content. Use
     `content_outline` as guidance when present.
   - **`action: deleted`** — remove the file at
     `{{ vars.skill_dir }}/<path>`.
3. Stay strictly within the plan. Any deviation requires the
   user to revise the plan first — there is no path here for
   "while I'm at it" cleanups, refactors, or naming changes.

## Output

Construct `output.yaml` (matching `schemas/files.yaml`) via
loom's schema-driven writer. `fs_write` is for the edited
skill files; the task output goes through `loom output`.

```bash
LOOM=~/.kiro/skills/home/loom/scripts/loom.sh
WD={{ run.workdir }}

$LOOM output init "$WD" --task modify-changes

$LOOM output add "$WD" --task modify-changes \
    --set 'files[].path=/abs/path/to/edited.md' \
    --set 'files[-1].action=modified' \
    --set 'files[].path=/abs/path/to/new-section.md' \
    --set 'files[-1].action=created' \
    --set 'files[].path=/abs/path/to/removed.md' \
    --set 'files[-1].action=deleted'
```

Syntax: `[]` appends, `[-1]` targets the last appended entry.
